segments.text: I'm excited about it.
Today is October the 16th, 1987.
I'm visiting with Dr. James F. McNamara, who has been at Texas A&M since 1976 and is a professor of educational psychology and educational administration.
Dr. McNamara is going to share some of his perceptions since his arrival at the College of Education about the changes and his visions

of the future possibly and as well as what is happening in the college right now and how impact, how change has impacted the College of Education and its goals and so forth and how it has changed as you arrived.
Yeah.
Let me make one correction for you on coming to Texas A&M.
I've been here twice.

I came to Texas A&M in September 1973 from the Advanced Study Center at the University of Oregon and stayed two years, sold everything I owned here, packed up all my baggage and went to Columbia University, never to see Texas A&M again.
One year later,
I was back at Texas A&M and have been here since September 76.
What's I think most important in that is that I came back for just one reason, to work with Dean Frank W. R. Huber.
That man had vision for the college and he knew the first laws of change.
that one needs to build a fiscally sound enterprise before one goes into all the ideas and nuances that would really put a college on the map.
The real specific of that is this.
We have today the benefits of Frank W.R. Huber, who funded almost everyone in the early years of the college on a 12-month appointment.
We are probably the only college in the United States that has the largest percentage of its tenure track professors on 12, not nine months, appointments.
And that was done in the very early years of the college with a whole lot of insight that the real first instrument for change is financial.
If I looked at it and looked at both of the deans that we had, I'd have to say that Frank W.R. Hubert built a fiscally sound college.
He did it without federal money, without state money, or without special state funding.
He did it all on money that accrued to the operating budget of the college, and we still
What is that money?
You're talking about non-soft money.
Yeah.
His idea was that you don't build a permanent college of education with soft money.
Soft money underwrites some ideas, but you really build a college with hard money.
And it's like fixed and variable expenditures.
He just thought that we needed a fixed expenditure for the college.
And college budgets are very labor intensive, and they require an enormous amount of money.
Hubert got that.
The second thing I think that's important with Hubert, and then I'd like to say just a little bit about the next theme.
Hubert handpicked almost every faculty member who came to A&M in the formative years.
Do you think he had a special something that he looked for in those people?
Oh, absolutely.
Do you see something that was across?
What is that?
I think Hubert had what he called the post-hole theory.
It was you invest special monies for change in individuals who are entrepreneurial and thinking and real agents for change, but able to venture.
A good example of a person that Hubert Post told in the early days came about the same time I did, is Bill Nash.
The whole gifted and talented movement was a personal investment in people such as Bill Nash.
Bill was not a researcher.
Bill was a program developer.
He had another job offer at the University of Chicago, but came to Texas A&M.
He was, at the time he came here, on a one-year appointment at Texas Southern University working with minorities and tried to advantage their opportunities for schooling.
I think the characteristics of Bill, and particularly his interest there, his programmability, his commitment to working with minorities, and last, but I would say most important, his brand name.
institution, the University of Georgia.
It's one of the key colleges of education in the United States that deals with creativity and assessment measures of creativity.
Bill had all those research skills.
Earlier in the college days, the dean tried to pollinate by picking up Hal Hawkins from Harvard, Bob Schutz from Stanford, and he was director of the lab school at Stanford.
He picked up Glenn Johnson, who was a graduate from Teachers College.
And in the 11th hour, 2300 for the military types, every one of these people were good researchers, but with a specific vision and a fairly clear-cut idea of where they wanted to be in the college.
Mike Ash was recruited, now the department head of Ed Psych, to get child development in those areas leveraged.
I came in educational administration to get research going in administration.
This is nuanced, but it's probably important when you listen to the tape and you go back.
I can tell you real quick, in about a minute or two, how I ended up at Texas A&M.
And it really all states Hubert's radar to find people with certain characteristics.
I had never heard of Texas A&M, but they were looking for a person to head up the planning, research, and evaluation efforts here in the college.
And they had a job description for a full professor.
I sat down and wrote one afternoon at the Advanced Studies Center five pages about what I thought planning, research, and evaluation should be in a college of education, sent it to Texas A&M,
and with only three years out of graduate school, asking for a full professorship.
Hubert hired me, never interviewed anyone else for the job, asked me to come and think on my feet in a seminar for the faculty without any presentation or forewarning.
Two years after I came to Texas A&M, I found out that the reason why I was brought to Texas A&M was one, the reasons were, one, because of the letter and the vision, but two, the verification.
His cousin was a professor of educational administration at the University of Kansas, or Kansas State.
And when my letter arrived with Hubert, he called his cousin,
And his cousin told him what my skills were, what I was doing at the Advanced Study Center, and that I was probably one of the largest possible outliers that could exist in any event.
Because 75 of my 90 hours in graduate preparation were all mathematics.
And that my three-year history was in research, both theoretical and empirical.
And he had checked through that far.
long before he had me here on the campus.
It was on the strength of that that he canceled the search.
But my example for your tape is that the man spent an enormous amount of effort locating profs.
If you look at the demography of that, the profs that he hired are still here.
By and large, 90% of the people that were hired
Between 1969 and 1976, when I came back to Texas A&M, are still here.
They're individually productive.
They not only wear a department hat, they wear a college hat.
And they sell their soul to the college, to its advancement.
They're personally renowned and recognized in their own fields.
The man just had an ingenious sense.
Thank you.
So not only did he develop a fiscally sound college, but in the process of doing that, he found the people.
That's what makes the college, is the people.
And when I came to Texas A&M, the first two years I was here, from this post-hoeing theory I gave you, he gave me $17,000 of unconverted money to use as I saw fit to advance research in college.
And long before some of the superstars like Vic Wilson, Gwyneth Badu, and Cecil Reynolds from our department, he was already investing in a couple of people.
Bill Nash is an example.
John Denton and I, in 1979, were given a whole summer off to do anything we wanted to do
that we thought was important to influence the future development of research in the college.
I took the whole summer off on full pay and went to the University of Michigan as a visiting scholar and learned survey research.
John went over to the Texas R&D Center in Austin.
Three years later, John was back here and was president of the Texas Association of Plain Evaluation Research.
And ever since that time, he's leveraged the advantage for research in the Southwest region for Texas A&M.
So then the mission of the teaching, research, and service, which is what the mission of the college is now, was very much in place at the time.
It actually started when the college started.
And has the emphasis shifted any from teaching, research, and service?
Yeah, yeah.
I would say that there's been a real growing emphasis on research.
Here's my model.
When I came here, I shared with Hubert that I thought it took 25 years to build a college of education of the stature of a Stanford, a Harvard, an Illinois, a Wisconsin, a Minnesota.
Are we going to get there?
Yeah, we're pretty close.
I said there were really three phases, and each of them had about a 10-year cycle.
But over a quarter of a century, that means some of those are overlapping, if you can visualize what I'm saying.
You can just put these three 10-year bars.
The first part of the plan to build a college is to have service.
And Hubert did that.
The next thing...
Well, I'm sorry, I really think the first piece of it is teaching.
I'm sorry, I didn't... And Hubert hired people who could really teach in graduate professional education.
And so the first ten years were really devoted to teaching.
Research was done off the end of the bench, so its weight was pretty small.
About seven or eight years down that 25-year cycle, he started to do some service work.
In the process of thinking of service, they started to think about evaluation designs, technical assistance.
And these things became the fodder and the lubricants that started the third cycle, which would be research.
So if you go back and look at the transactions of the college, you can use the model I just gave you, and you can see that 20 years later, all three of those things are in place.
Teaching is pretty well anchored.

Services growing even now with the school university collaborative some of your service activity that be linked to the minority recruitment The whole gifted and talented program service area the special ed service areas A lot of the service is pretty well anchored and it's gearing to research Now the research is almost in place and what we're finding is a lot of the theoretical research we work on is not research
that came from the ideas of individuals, but rather are coming out of this joint collaborative college mission.
Victor Wilson's a good example.
Vic started to work with the computer program and the gifted and talented and working with very young youth.
This is a professor?
Yeah, Vic Wilson's a fellow in extracurricular and he's one of our statisticians.
Vic is probably the, he's one of the top three researchers of the college.
But Vic started to work with the service activities of the Gifted and Talented Program.
And from that now, they're doing some very theoretical research relating to measurement, which will detect in early stages, in early youth, genius.
Pat Alexander's involved in that.
Now, it's so naturally confounded with these service things, the second or the third stage, that you never know it.
Tell me who the three top researchers are considered in the college.
I know you're one of them.
That's a tough one.
That's a really tough one.
Well, there's a lot.
I say that Vic's top because Vic...
is as theoretical as any researcher in the college.
And he's also as practical as any researcher in the college.
His portfolio of insights and skills are just as valuable theoretically as they are empirically.
If you ask me for the top three, there are a couple in the college who are very good theoretically.
have no interest in collaborative research in the field.
They are sort of what they call in mathematics and science is pioneering.
They're doing the frontier research.
Well, I think you will be my only source, or my best source, on the researching part of the college.
So I would give you those insights.
I would say, if you would have asked me this question in 1978, or even ask Hubert,
Hubert would have said John Denton and Jim McNamara.
And those were the two that he invested in.
Since that time, I'd like to say that there are about five or six that I would put in an orbit and not rank order.
And that would be Victor Wilson, John Denton, Gwyneth Padoo, Cecil Reynolds, Ernie Goetz, and Jim McNamara.
Now, notice that the largest concentration of those researchers is at Ed Psych.
So if you really want to follow the research transactions of the college, the premier push came out of Ed Psych.
Now, that was one of the most, I wouldn't say devastating, but defeating notions for Hubert.
Because Frank Hubert wanted the educational administration department in this college to be premier.
All his training was in administration, both educational and public administration, and in history and governance.
And originally, he thought that the ed admin department here would be just an outstanding research department.
I would say it's a very good service department, the principal center being a good example.
Of some of the recent, yeah.
And another really superior example would be the almost $2 million that were invested in the community education center.
None of that money, incidentally, was ever sidetracked, like corporations would do with about 5% of their working capital put in R&D.
That never happened in the Mott Foundation efforts.
but a tremendous service effort.
The premier research department, I'll say it again, it's like he didn't expect that originally.
If you move on now, and then I'll come back and take any specific questions you want.
When Corrigan came to the college, Corrigan inherited a fiscally sound college.

And I would go so far as to say, in terms of faculty morale and underwriting, financial underwriting, the best and the most visibly sound college in Asia, given all those full-time employment, 12-month contracts.
He also inherited an enormous amount of talent.
His leadership style was so dramatically different than Corrigan's that people started to rise to the occasion.
He had the little near mnemonic which said, sharing, daring, and caring.
And his objective, I think, which was embedded in all that rhetoric, was to make, to create two colleges.
A formal college where people reside, departments, and where they get their money.
And then what I would call the idea college,
And the idea college was the inquiry groups.
So inquiry groups are like departments, but they're adhocracies in Toffler's sense, rather than formal departments.
Are they still very active?
I mean, I know he initiated, but have they maintained that momentum?
I would suggest that you couldn't put your finger on the inquiry groups as they were established.
That was my meaning in the autocracies.
What Corrigan wanted to do was to bring researchers with common interests together, quite independent of the departments, and to get them speaking with each other.
and getting to undertake some common endeavors.
And did that happen?
Oh, yeah.
That happened.
And it was a very, very effective strategy.
But I don't think the inquiry group orientation needed to be long-lasting.
It was more a development of a kinship, a professional kinship.
Hi.
Hi, Ann.
Yeah, I'm right in the middle of an interview.
OK, can I come back later?
Yeah, about 3.30, I'll be around.
No, those things are not very active for my money, but what people have done is come together and are working on common things.
Is that a collaborative effort within departments or with other colleges?
I think to even link it to departments is really counterproductive to what the inquiry groups accomplished.
It brought people together with people.
That's what I meant by the kinship.
But not necessarily even...
people within, or are they all in the college?
Are they working with other people?
Oh, yeah.
No, they're predominantly in the college.

And I would say that several of the department heads in the college systematically resisted the whole notion of inquiry because it made information and scholarly productivity and activity valuable in its own right.
Did it conflict with their philosophy?
Did each department have a very distinct philosophy that conflicted with that?
Or was the philosophy the same, but just the way they went about doing things?
Oh, I think entirely different.
Each department?
Entirely different.
I would say that Ed Psych, for example, just wanted to work with inquiry in every way they could.
And you'll find its faculty were in every inquiry group.
On the other hand, I can tell you two departments that almost penalized faculty for joining inquiry groups.
Now, I would say that's the difference in philosophy.
That's interesting.
And when you turn the tape recorder off, I'll tell you the departments.
But I'll tell you where you can get that information and answer that question in a really neat way.
Dave Erlandson did a study on that.
And what you find is I think there are four different, a couple of different profiles.
And there are even a couple of different types of inquiry groups that were designated and emerging.
I chaired one of the designated inquiry groups that led to this whole computer idea in the college.
It was called the Inquiry Group on Research Assistance in Computer Technology.
And that stayed together for about four years.
And we were very instrumental outside of the department structure in recommending how money got spent for computers.
And in some cases, the faculty were much more likely than departments to pool their resources when they needed big things.
Departments compete.
Inquiry group members pool.
It's a nice contrast.
And the dean sort of sanctioned that.
He just sort of fanned the fumes, the flames, and worked that.
And it really upset some of the department heads.
Well, because it was so, I mean, it had not been done before, and it was just such a drastic change, like you said.
And that's unique to this dean.
And that's why I'm looking at this study as two distinct eras, with the interim year with Dr. Limbacher.
But it was definitely a Hubert era, and there is now a Corrigan era, and they each are unique in their own.
Well, I would say Corrigan's success was pretty well, could be predicted from the legacy that was left to him.
Mm-hmm.
from prior administration.
I mean, not only that Chancellor Hubert, but the endorsement of the university.
OK. Now, from going from administration to the student body, and we're hearing a lot now about the standards at A&M and how it's affecting the students that we get now.
It has grown tremendously, even since you've been here.
What do you see as far as, has it affected the way you get to work with students now that there's so many more students and now that they're coming in?
with much higher standards are getting higher and higher.
Are we weeding out people that really need to be in this college?
Do you think the standards are higher?
For graduate instruction?
Now than they were 10 years ago?
Because I don't think that's true.
No, I guess I'm going more with the fact that the standards for admission are now going up higher.
Graduate admission?
No, undergraduate.
No, graduate is not.
That's right.

You are strictly... Last year was the first time I taught a graduate course at Texas A&M, and I worked with some of the math scholar students, undergraduate math scholar, and will continue to work with them.
That was the first undergraduate?
First undergraduate course.
I'm in two departments, neither one of which has an undergraduate program.
But I would say that there are only a couple of occasions that I'd point to where the graduate admissions standards are tougher now.
And there's one very obvious case in the college.
That's Ed Psych Counseling Program.
person that they select on an annual basis for a four-year residency to complete a degree, there are seven to eight people standing in line waiting for that position.
I don't know if you know that they're that good.
Fantastic.
Another case where the enrollment standards have jumped astronomically is in school psych.
I mean, the quality of students, school psych.
And that's a new program.
Now, both of those are APA approved.
In universities, there are four types of APA programs, clinical, school and counseling, and industrial psych.
Those are the only four basic.
We have two of the four in this department.
And some of the most recent ratings on both counseling and school psych say we're up there running with the best in the country.
Now, those things have really changed the type of students that I've worked with.
I find that these students, although they come originally without a large predilection and appetite for research, very quickly shift gears.
So that was something that you mentioned earlier, too, about the fact that how we are perceived by other universities and outside this college.
So you've answered it a couple of times now by what you're talking about the students and then also what you referenced before about the fact that we're almost there with these goals that you
that you kind of projected back 25 or 20 years ago or 18 years ago?
I'd say we're almost there, but I can tell you some things that are really dragging weight on making this a research university.
What's that?
I'd say it's the Ed Admin Department.
The what?
The Ed Admin Department.
I think the Ed Admin Department is still in a service mode in terms of students.
In fact, I think there are over 200 students who are just sort of, don't quote me on this,
But there's a large number of students, I've heard the number 200, who are not degree students but are certification students.
Now, these folks are shopping around.
They shop for courses.
They'll take anything we offer in San Antonio, if they're from San Antonio, and then work it to a degree, to a certification plan.
They'll take what they can get here.
But by and large, they're not degree students.
So do you see that as a holding back?
If the objective is to become a major research university.
I'm not saying that's just... And is it?
Is that the objective?
That was Dean Corrigan.
I mean, he mentioned that in his initial...
I would say any time the rhetoric leaves the college and moves towards the university, that you're going to get that said.
Mm-hmm.
Sure.
I think Corrigan's idea, if he speaks to central administration, he's got to get on the same wavelength, in the same orbit that the university's in.
So the rhetoric that way is going to go.
It'll go.

I would think that the rhetoric in a college, at least some of Corrigan's rhetoric, would suggest that there's an effort to create one profession, and that people in the schools and people in the university ought to be more formally linked.
that they're in a profession.
And what the college should be having as its objective is the betterment of the profession.
And the betterment of the profession, if you follow its logic, can't be any better than the quality of what we do for students in any kind of academic environment.
But I've heard that rhetoric.
And that's not directly influenced by research.
The connection between research and the day-to-day world of schools is much more immediate than immediate.
I think we cheat a little bit on that one, to call it college research.
But I still don't think we're in the full third phase of what it takes in the first quarter century to make an orange university.
But we're getting there.
And is there a search out there for people that will help to get there, to help us to get there?
I mean, is there an active search for kinds of people that are interested in those kinds of areas where it will?
I'd say that efforts in the Development Council
our efforts to try and find more resources and more opportunity and more advocacy for the research, for the research members of the college.
And for the service, but for the research, yeah.
I see that as a useful transaction.
I think the school-university collaborative research that we've started is probably one of the most exciting things that has come down the pike.
And I think it...
Sorry I didn't make it to that meeting, but I do want to keep in touch with that.
I do think that that's going to have a dramatic impact in the next three years in the college.
I think it might replace some of the activities of inquiry group.

What are some of the highlights, looking back now, in the past and in the present, I'm interested in what you feel have been your greatest contributions, which obviously are in the research field, but maybe a couple of insights or observations that you have, and you shared some really neat ones today, that as somebody looks at this maybe 20 or 30 years from now and looks at
Yeah, here's some tangents that you probably wouldn't get elsewhere.
Okay, that's what I want.
When we had the search for Dean Carter, it was...
Hold on, let me transfer the...
